<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-235-159 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 345 124</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 31 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Martin Marietta announces Army contract. (Martin Marietta Corp. tostudy effects of electromagnetic radiation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Martin Marietta Corp. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    ML.andO;Topic:     United States. ArmyDefense ContractsElectromagnetic RadiationElectromagnetic interferenceResearch and Development.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MARTIN MARIETTA ANNOUNCES ARMY CONTRACT 01/31/91 BETHESDA, MARYLAND, U.S.A.,andO;1991 JAN 31 (NB) -- Martin Marietta Corporation has announced that it hasbeen selected to participate in a U.S.andP;  Army program designed to assess howelectromagnetic radiation affects communications and electronic systems.andM;Under the contract, Martin Marietta Simulation Systems at Colorado Springs,Colo., under a subcontract to Atlantic Research Corporation, will providecomputer simulation and modeling capability and database management for theArmy's Electromagnetic Environmental Test Facility at Ft.andP;  Huachucha, Ariz.andO;Martin Marietta stated that its workshare is valued at approximately $7million.andM;In its statement announcing the contract, Martin Marietta explained thatelectromagnetic interference can be caused naturally by sunspots or byman-made objects, such as microwave transmission towers or high-energyelectric power lines.andP;  Using computer simulation, the Army will be able tostudy the causes and performance impact of such interference on militarysystems.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19910131/Press Contact: Pat McGinn,Martin Marietta, 719-594-7008)</TEXT></DOC>